      Charter airline regulatory arbitrage
   =20
 =20

No, wrong, this might be my favorite business origin story of all time:

Wilcox got the idea for the service in what=E2=80=99s possibly the least gl=
amorous business origin story of all time. Combing through US Federal Aviat=
ion Administration regulations, he learned that while scheduled flights wit=
h more than nine seats have to meet onerous safety and security requirement=
s, on-demand public charters have separate, less stringent rules. Though, t=
hey can=E2=80=99t specify flight times or cities or sell single seats.
To get around that, Wilcox decided to create two companies that would work =
together: One would make a flight schedule and sell tickets, and a second w=
ould fly the aircraft on specified routes at set times and dates. In realit=
y, though, it=E2=80=99s one entity working behind the scenes.
=E2=80=9CI spent months without sleep, just looking at all the rules, looki=
ng for ways why it couldn=E2=80=99t be done,=E2=80=9D he said on a clear Fe=
bruary day in a hangar at Dallas Love Field. =E2=80=9CEvery single person w=
e talked to said, =E2=80=98No, you can=E2=80=99t do it.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D T=
hen US regulators signed off on his idea. =E2=80=9CSo we did it.=E2=80=9D

That is from a Bloomberg story about JSX, a charter airline that Alex Wilco=
x started after sleepless nights of reading FAA regulations. He read and re=
ad and read the rules until he found an arbitrage.
  [3]
 If you have an airline that sells and operates scheduled flights, you are =
subject to high and expensive safety standards. But if you=C2=A0divide=C2=
=A0that airline into two bits, one that operates flights and another that s=
erves as a front end to set schedules and sell tickets, each bit is subject=
 to lower standards. If the two bits are owned by the same corporate entity=
 and coordinate together, then the result is something that looks like a si=
ngle normal airline=C2=A0to customers, but looks like two separate less-reg=
ulated entities=C2=A0to regulators.=C2=A0
I guess this is not technically a=C2=A0finance=C2=A0story, but half of what=
 I write about has the form =E2=80=9Cif you do Thing X it gets Regulatory T=
reatment Y, but if you divide it into Things X1 and X2, the combination is =
the same as Thing X but gets better Regulatory Treatment Z.=E2=80=9D We hav=
e talked about treating loans as purchases, about derivatives to get around=
 stock ownership limits, about special purpose acquisition companies to get=
 around initial public offering rules, about brokered deposits as a way to =
get around   FDIC insurance limits, about slicing up fund investments to ge=
t better ratings. I am sure that=C2=A0some=C2=A0of these businesses origina=
ted exactly as JSX=E2=80=99s did: Somebody thought, =E2=80=9Cwell, this rul=
ebook is long and boring, so probably nobody has read it all the way throug=
h, and if I do, money might come flying out.=E2=80=9D Just a great way to f=
ind a business model.
Incidentally, we talked last week=C2=A0about a related but slightly differe=
nt business model. Avid Bioservices Inc. had a convertible bond, and it mad=
e a small mistake in its administration of the bonds, and if you read the b=
ond documents very carefully and paid close attention and had a good unders=
tanding of convertible market practice, you could have made a fair amount o=
f money for yourself, and caused a lot of trouble for Avid, by calling atte=
ntion to the mistake. Somebody did. I wrote:
That=E2=80=99s the thing about efficient markets, man.=C2=A0You=C2=A0might =
quite reasonably find section 4.06(e) of this 2021 convertible bond indentu=
re, the section covering restricted transfer legends, boring, and not want =
to think about it.=C2=A0Avid=C2=A0quite reasonably found it boring, and did=
 not think about it. But for someone who=C2=A0did=C2=A0find it interesting =
enough to pay attention, there was $7 million of prize money just lying aro=
und for the taking.
That is the small-scale version of all of these regulatory arbitrage busine=
sses: If you read boring rules and think really hard about them, you can wi=
n monetary prizes.=C2=A0
Byrne Hobart also wrote about Avid last week, and he made another point:
Right now, it's suddenly gotten much easier to do this at scale: you can un=
leash LLMs on indenture agreements, and try to find edge cases that the com=
pany didn't think of or notice. These will all be technicalities in practic=
e; in the Avid case, if the restriction had been a big deal to the note own=
er, they probably would have noticed right away. But, perhaps coincidentall=
y, they only noticed after the newly-widespread availability of tools that =
can trawl through vast amounts of text to extract useful information.
I don=E2=80=99t know if the explanation for the Avid situation is really =
=E2=80=9Csome hedge fund used an artificial intelligence=C2=A0large languag=
e model to look through convertible bond indentures to find profitable mist=
akes=E2=80=9D; as a former converts structurer myself, I would like to thin=
k that some former converts structurer found this trade using general marke=
t knowledge and connoisseurship. But the larger point is right: An LLM prob=
ably can read the boring documents for you and spot the issues. And if =E2=
=80=9Cfind profitable mistakes in bond indentures=E2=80=9D is a useful thin=
g to ask your LLM to do, then maybe so is =E2=80=9Cfind profitable loophole=
s in aviation regulations and tell me what businesses to start to exploit t=
hem.=E2=80=9D
Anyway the Bloomberg JSX story goes on:

All that growth might now be the company=E2=80=99s undoing.
The FAA says its review of rules for public charter carriers like JSX came =
=E2=80=9Cin light of recent high-volume operations=E2=80=9D that =E2=80=9Ca=
ppear to be offered to the public as essentially indistinguishable from=E2=
=80=9D commercial carriers. The =E2=80=9Csize, scope, frequency and complex=
ity=E2=80=9D of public charter operations like JSX has =E2=80=9Cgrown signi=
ficantly over the past 10 years,=E2=80=9D the agency wrote in an August=C2=
=A0filing.

Ah well. Nothing lasts forever; on to the next business model.

