   =20
      Quants
   =20
 =20

Another classic way to set up a business is to go work for a big sophistica=
ted financial firm that has built a good business by being the smartest and=
 fastest at applying high-tech methods to squeeze out the last penny in hyp=
ercompetitive liquid financial markets, spend some time there learning the =
techniques, and then leave for a sleepier market where the competition is w=
eaker and spreads are wider. This describes, like, 90% of crypto markets, f=
or better and worse. But here=E2=80=99s a Wall Street Journal article about=
 quant traders=C2=A0in China=E2=80=99s stock market:

The launch of China=E2=80=99s quant industry goes back to around 2010, when=
 a generation of Chinese-born traders returned home after working for some =
of the biggest U.S. hedge funds. In the wake of the global financial crisis=
, when China=E2=80=99s economy was booming while the Western world suffered=
, setting up a fund in mainland China was a natural choice for these trader=
s.
Millennium, a New York-based fund, was a particularly strong breeding groun=
d for talent. Wang Chen and Yao Qicong, who had both worked there, moved to=
 China to help set up Ubiquant Investment in 2012. Ma Zhiyu left to set up =
Ningbo Lingjun Investment Management Partnership in 2014. The two funds are=
 now among the biggest quants in China, with Ubiquant managing more than $7=
 billion.

At some level, =E2=80=9Cwe will take the techniques we learned in the most =
competitive markets in finance and apply them to a sleepy backwater=E2=80=
=9D is an obviously appealing pitch, and it made a lot of fortunes in crypt=
o and also in Chinese stock markets. But =E2=80=9Cwe will apply the statist=
ical techniques we learned in a market with a ton of historical data throug=
h various market regimes, and apply them to a less liquid market that start=
ed 20 minutes ago=E2=80=9D has some obvious flaws, too:

China=E2=80=99s quants had a few problems not shared by their U.S. counterp=
arts.
For one thing, the country=E2=80=99s rapid emergence as an economic powerho=
use meant these funds didn=E2=80=99t have decades of data to fall back on, =
a major failing for firms that rely on data mining to identify trades. The =
even bigger problem was China=E2=80=99s great intangible: the whims of the =
government.
The algorithms used by quant funds digest large amounts of historical data =
and take advantage of repeatable patterns. While China=E2=80=99s stock=E2=
=80=93market interventions have become more frequent in recent months, they=
 are still not regular occurrences.
=E2=80=9CQuants are just really bad at coping when something suddenly chang=
es,=E2=80=9D said Phillip Wool, head of research at money manager Rayliant =
Global Advisors. =E2=80=9CIf you have a policy intervention that changes th=
e rules of the game, these models just aren=E2=80=99t that adaptable.=E2=80=
=9D

And:
The country=E2=80=99s two biggest stock exchanges and its securities regula=
tor launched a widespread clampdown on quants in late February, tightening =
the rules governing the sector and temporarily banning two funds from tradi=
ng altogether.=C2=A0
If you learned your trade at Millennium, you probably did=C2=A0not learn to=
 put=C2=A0that=C2=A0much weight on the risk of regulators banning you from =
trading when the market goes down, because that was not a regular occurrenc=
e at Millennium.=C2=A0

