: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Wall Street Journal ar=
ticle</a> about quant traders=C2=A0in China=E2=80=99s stock market:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The launch of China=E2=80=99s quant industry g=
oes back to around 2010, when a generation of Chinese-born traders returned=
 home after working for some of the biggest U.S. hedge funds. In the wake o=
f the global financial crisis, when China=E2=80=99s economy was booming whi=
le the Western world suffered, setting up a fund in mainland China was a na=
tural choice for these traders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Millennium, a New York-based fund, was a parti=
cularly strong breeding ground for talent. Wang Chen and Yao Qicong, who ha=
d both worked there, moved to China to help set up Ubiquant Investment in 2=
012. Ma Zhiyu left to set up Ningbo Lingjun Investment Management Partnersh=
ip in 2014. The two funds are now among the biggest quants in China, with U=
biquant managing more than $7 billion.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some level, =E2=80=9Cwe will take the techn=
iques we learned in the most competitive markets in finance and apply them =
to a sleepy backwater=E2=80=9D is an obviously appealing pitch, and it made=
 a lot of fortunes in crypto and also in Chinese stock markets. But =E2=80=
=9Cwe will apply the statistical techniques we learned in a market with a t=
on of historical data through various market regimes, and apply them to a l=
ess liquid market that started 20 minutes ago=E2=80=9D has some obvious fla=
ws, too:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">China=E2=80=99s quants had a few problems not =
shared by their U.S. counterparts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For one thing, the country=E2=80=99s rapid eme=
rgence as an economic powerhouse meant these funds didn=E2=80=99t have deca=
des of data to fall back on, a major failing for firms that rely on data mi=
ning to identify trades. The even bigger problem was China=E2=80=99s great =
intangible: the whims of the government.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The algorithms used by quant funds digest larg=
e amounts of historical data and take advantage of repeatable patterns. Whi=
le China=E2=80=99s stock=E2=80=93market interventions have become more freq=
uent in recent months, they are still not regular occurrences.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CQuants are just really bad at coping =
when something suddenly changes,=E2=80=9D said Phillip Wool, head of resear=
ch at money manager Rayliant Global Advisors. =E2=80=9CIf you have a policy=
 intervention that changes the rules of the game, these models just aren=E2=
=80=99t that adaptable.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The country=E2=80=99s two biggest =
stock exchanges and its securities regulator launched a widespread clampdow=
n on quants in late February, tightening the rules governing the sector and=
 temporarily banning two funds from trading altogether.=C2=A0</p></blockquo=
te>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you learned your trade at Millennium, you p=
